# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: advocate-general-for-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1802 United Kingdom general election** was the first general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held from 5 July 1802 to 28 August 1802, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the new Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The first Parliament had been composed of members of the former Parliaments of the Kingdom of Great Britain and the Kingdom of Ireland.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The Parliament of Great Britain held its last general election in 1796.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The final election for the Parliament of Ireland was held in 1797.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The first united Parliament was dissolved on 29 June 1802.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 31 August 1802, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Prime Minister Henry Addington led a war-time administration of pro-government Whigs and Tories, collectively referred to as the "Addingtonians", in office during part of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The previous Prime Minister, William Pitt the Younger, had been out of office since 1801.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] King George III had forced Pitt to resign by refusing to agree to Catholic emancipation (allowing Catholics to sit in Parliament) following the Union.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] His faction in Parliament was generally supportive of the Addington ministry, before becoming increasingly opposed over the course of the Parliamentary term.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] On 25 March 1802 the Treaty of Amiens brought about peace with France, with which Great Britain had been at war since 1792.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The international situation remained uneasy and a renewal of war was still possible.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The Treaty was supported by a strong majority of the Commons, only meeting strong opposition from the small group of 'New Opposition' or Grenvillite parliamentarians, formed around Lord Grenville and led in the Commons by William Windham, both former cabinet ministers under Pitt.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] In the election the combination of the followers of Addington and Pitt comfortably defeated both the 'Old' Opposition Foxites under Charles James Fox and the 'New' Opposition of Lord Grenville.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite his reluctance to foster a personal faction and the presence of some of his followers in both support and opposition to Addington, Pitt retained an unclear personal following of around fifty-seven MPs.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was a decidedly quiet affair owing to the general popularity of Addington's diplomatic and peace policies.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Two notable results occurred in the urban constituencies of Middlesex and Norwich.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] At Middlesex the Radical Francis Burdett defeated William Mainwaring, a supporter of Addington.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] After an inquiry Burdett was unseated and defeated narrowly at a by-election by Mainwaring's son, George Boulton Mainwaring.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] At Norwich Windham and fellow conservative incumbent John Frere were defeated by Radical William Smith and Foxite Robert Fellowes in a campaign where Windham's opposition to peace had weakened his popularity.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Windham was promptly returned for St Mawes, a pocket borough of Lord Grenville's brother, Lord Buckingham.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] At this period there was not one election day.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] After receiving a writ (a royal command) for the election to be held, the local returning officer fixed the election timetable for the particular constituency or constituencies he was concerned with.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Polling in seats with contested elections could continue for many days.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The election took place over a period of almost two months.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contested elections was 5 July to 28 August 1802.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Monmouthshire (1 County constituency with 2 MPs and one single member Borough constituency) is included in Wales in these tables.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Sources for this period may include the county in England.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1806 United Kingdom general election** was the second general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held from 29 October 1806 to 17 December 1806, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election took place in a situation of considerable uncertainty about the future of British politics, following the sudden death of William Pitt the Younger and the formation of the Ministry of all the Talents.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Parliament was dissolved on 24 October 1806.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 13 December 1806, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The maximum term could be and normally was curtailed, by the monarch dissolving the Parliament, before its term expired.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Since the previous general election fighting in the Napoleonic Wars with France had resumed in 1803.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Tory Prime Minister Henry Addington had resigned in 1804.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] William Pitt the Younger formed a new coalition of pro-government Whig and Tory politicians to prosecute the war.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The opposition Whigs, led by Charles James Fox, continued to oppose the government.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] They were strengthened by a group of Pitt's former supporters (such as his cousin William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville) who had aligned themselves with Fox in opposition to Addington after 1802 and who did not accompany Pitt and his other friends back to office in 1804.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] When Pitt died on 23 January 1806 a new ministry was formed by Grenville.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] It included Fox and Addington (now ennobled as the 1st Viscount Sidmouth) as well as other leading political figures of the day.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] However it did not include George Canning, who had inherited the leadership of Pitt's faction in the House of Commons or the Duke of Portland who led it in the House of Lords.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] This government was known as the Ministry of all the Talents.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] An attempt was made to end the Napoleonic Wars by negotiation.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Grenville also tried to strengthen the government, but was unable to persuade the Pittites to join him either as a body or by detaching some leading figures.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The Prime Minister was not prepared to exclude Fox and his friends as the Pittites wanted.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Lord Grenville then decided to hold a general election to strengthen his government.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The Talents were in office at the time of this election and continued after it, but the Ministry was weakened by the death of Fox on 13 September 1806.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The election itself was a disappointment.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] In the eighteenth century a government with the King's backing could expect to make substantial gains at an election.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] However Pitt's financial reforms had weakened the ability of the Treasury to manipulate election results.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Foord estimated that the Ministry only gained about thirty seats by the 1806 appeal to the country.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contested elections was 29 October to 17 December 1806.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1807 United Kingdom general election** was the third general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held from 4 May 1807 to 9 June 1807.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The third United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 29 April 1807.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 22 June 1807, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the 1806 election the Ministry of all the Talents, a coalition of the Foxite and Grenvillite Whig and Addingtonite Tory factions, with William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville, as Prime Minister continued in office.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] It had attempted to end the Napoleonic Wars by negotiation.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The faction formerly led by William Pitt the Younger, before his death in January 1806, were the major group in opposition to the Talents' Ministry.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] George Canning in the House of Commons and the Duke of Portland in the House of Lords were at the head of this opposition.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] Grenville and his cabinet lost the support of King George III by trying to legislate to permit Roman Catholics to serve as Army and Navy officers.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] When ministers refused to give the King written confirmation that they would not raise the Catholic issue again, he decided to find new servants.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The elderly Duke of Portland was asked to form a new ministry in March 1807.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] Portland had been the Whig Prime Minister before, in the 1780s, so now he described himself as the Whig Prime Minister of a Tory ministry.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] After Pitt's death the younger Pittites increasingly began calling themselves the Tory Party, whether they had previously belonged to the Whig or Tory tradition.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] This was an important stage in the development of a more organised two-party system, which reduced the influence of factions and connections in British politics.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The new ministers found it difficult to manage a House of Commons recently elected to support their opponents.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] A month into the new government the King granted a dissolution.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The government policies of opposing Catholic relief and supporting the traditional powers of the King proved popular (at least with the restricted section of the population enfranchised in elections for the unreformed House of Commons).
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] After the election the government programme was approved by a vote of 350 to 155 in the House of Commons, demonstrating the substantial gains ministers had made in the election.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contested elections was 4 May to 9 June 1807.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1812 United Kingdom general election** was the fourth general election after the Union of Great Britain and Ireland, held from 5 October 1812 to 10 November 1812, taking place at the height of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The fourth United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 29 September 1812, four months after the Earl of Liverpool succeeded to the premiership following the assassination of Spencer Perceval.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 24 November 1812, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the 1807 election the Pittite Tory ministry, led as prime minister by the Duke of Portland (who still claimed to be a Whig), continued to prosecute the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] At the core of the opposition were the Foxite Whigs, led since the death of Fox in 1806 by Earl Grey (known by the courtesy title of Viscount Howick and a member of the House of Commons from 1806 to 1807).
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] However, as Foord observes: "the affairs of the party during most of this period were in a state of uncertainty and confusion".
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Grey was not the commanding leader Fox had been.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] After Grey inherited his peerage and went to the House of Lords in 1807, the party leadership in the House of Commons was extremely weak.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The Grenvillites, associated with the Whig Prime Minister before Portland, William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville, were also in opposition but were of less significance than the Foxites.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite this Grenville was recognised as the first Leader of the Opposition in the House of Lords.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] A relative of Grey's wife, George Ponsonby, was proposed to Whig MPs by Grey and Grenville as the Whig leader in the House of Commons.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Ponsonby was the first person recognised as the official Leader of *the* Opposition in the House of Commons, as opposed to the leader of *an* opposition faction.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] He proved to be incompetent but could not be persuaded to resign.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Until 1812 the Tory faction associated with another former prime minister, Henry Addington, 1st Viscount Sidmouth, and were also out of office.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The smallest component of the opposition were the Radicals, who were a largely middle-class group of reformers.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] They had philosophical differences with the more aristocratic Whigs, but usually ended up voting with them in Parliament.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1809 Portland, whose health was failing, resigned.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Tory Prime Minister was Spencer Perceval.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] In April 1812 he brought Sidmouth into the cabinet.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] A month later, on 11 May 1812, Perceval was assassinated.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The premiership passed to the Earl of Liverpool, who failed to attract Grenville.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] This was a further stage in the development of a two-party system—just about all Tories supported the government and all Whigs opposed it.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election of 1812 returned the Tories to power for another term.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] An example of what happened in the 1812 election was the Irish constituency of Westmeath.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Walker confirms the date of election was 24 October 1812.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Stooks Smith indicates that there were three days of polling, during which time 950 electors came to the hustings and voted.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The polling in the Berkshire election of 1812 went on for 15 days (with 1,992 electors voting).
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contests in the general election was 5 October to 10 November 1812.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1818 United Kingdom general election** was the 5th general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held on 17 June 1818 to 18 July 1818.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] It saw the Whigs gain a few seats, but the Tories under the Earl of Liverpool retained a majority of around 90 seats.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whigs were divided over their response to growing social unrest and the introduction of the Corn Laws.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The fifth United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 10 June 1818.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 4 August 1818, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The sixth Parliament lasted only about a year and a half, as King George III's death on 29 January 1820 triggered a dissolution of Parliament.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Tory leader was the Earl of Liverpool, who had been prime minister since his predecessor's assassination in 1812.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Tory Leader of the House of Commons was Robert Stewart, Viscount Castlereagh.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whig Party had long suffered from weak leadership, particularly in the House of Commons.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] At the time of the general election, the Earl Grey was the leading figure amongst the Whig peers.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The last Whig Prime Minister, the Lord Grenville, had retired from active politics in 1817.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] It was likely that Earl Grey would have been invited to form a government, had the Whigs come to power, although in this era the monarch rather than the governing party decided which individual would be prime minister.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons, until his death in 1817, was George Ponsonby, Lady Grey's uncle.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] About a year after Ponsonby's death, George Tierney reluctantly became the recognised Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] However, after 1819 he did not carry out the functions of leader although he retained the title.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1820 United Kingdom general election** was held on 6 March 1820 to 14 April 1820, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] Triggered by the death of King George III, it produced the first parliament of the reign of his successor, King George IV.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] It was held shortly after the Radical War in Scotland and the Cato Street Conspiracy.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] In this atmosphere, the Tories under the Earl of Liverpool were able to win a substantial majority over the Whigs.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The sixth United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 29 February 1820.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 21 April 1820, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The maximum term could be and normally was curtailed, by the monarch dissolving the Parliament before its term expired.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] Liverpool had led his party to two general election victories before that of 1820.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whig Party continued to suffer from weak leadership, particularly in the House of Commons.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] It was likely that Grey would have been invited to form a government, had the Whigs come to power, although in this era the monarch rather than the governing party decided which individual would be prime minister.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons, George Tierney, was successful at first after the Whig gains at the 1818 general election.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] However, on 18 May 1819, Tierney moved a motion in the House of Commons for a committee on the state of the nation.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] Foord comments that "this defeat put an effective end to Tierney's leadership".
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] However he continued to be the nominal leader at the time of the 1820 election.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] It was triggered by the death of King George III.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election took place between the first contest on 6 March and the last contest on 14 April 1820.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1826 United Kingdom general election** was the 7th general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held on 7 June 1826 to 12 July 1826, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] It saw the Tories under the Earl of Liverpool win a landslide victory over the Whigs.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In Ireland, liberal Protestant candidates favouring Catholic emancipation, backed by the Catholic Association, achieved significant gains.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The seventh United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 2 June 1826.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 25 July 1826, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] As of 2024, the Earl of Liverpool remains the most recent prime minister to have won four successive elections.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Liverpool had led his party to three general election victories before that of 1826.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The Tory Leader of the House of Commons until 1822, when he committed suicide, was Robert Stewart.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] He was known by the courtesy title of Viscount Castlereagh, until he inherited his father's Irish peerage and became the 2nd Marquess of Londonderry in 1821.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Londonderry was replaced as leader by George Canning, who remained Leader of the House of Commons in 1826.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1824 the Earl Grey gave up the formal Whig leadership in the Lords, although he remained the most prominent Whig peer.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Grey asked his friends to look to the leadership of the Marquess of Lansdowne.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Although Lansdowne performed the functions of leader, he did not accept the title.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] At the time of the general election, Grey was still the leading figure amongst the Whig peers.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] It was likely that he would have been invited to form a government, had the Whigs come to power, although in this era the monarch rather than the governing party decided which individual would be prime minister.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons at the previous general election, George Tierney, disclaimed the leadership on 23 January 1821.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] No new Whig leader emerged during the rest of the Parliament.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] There had been significant developments in Irish politics since the 1820 general election.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Whilst Catholics in Ireland—who met the normal property qualifications—had been permitted to vote since before the Union, they were still not eligible to sit in the United Kingdom Parliament.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The right for Catholics to serve in Parliament was known as a measure of Catholic emancipation.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1823, Daniel O'Connell started a campaign for repeal of the Act of Union, and took Catholic Emancipation as his rallying call, establishing the Catholic Association.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] From 1826, the Catholic Association began to support pro-emancipation candidates in elections.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The Association used its money and manpower to campaign for candidates to be elected into Parliament, to pressure the government from within to pass Catholic emancipation.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election took place between the first contest on 7 June and the last contest on 12 July 1826.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1821 the borough of Grampound in Cornwall was disenfranchised for corruption.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Its two seats were transferred to the county of Yorkshire, which from this general election became a four-seat constituency.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The **Office of the Advocate General for Scotland** is a ministerial department of the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The position is currently occupied by Catherine Smith, Baroness Smith of Cluny.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of Advocate General for Scotland was created in 1999 by the Scotland Act 1998 to be the chief legal adviser to the United Kingdom Government on Scots law.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] This function had previously been carried out by the Lord Advocate and Solicitor General for Scotland, who were transferred to the Scottish Government on the establishment of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of the Advocate General for Scotland should not be confused with that of "His Majesty's Advocate", which is the term used for the Lord Advocate in Scottish criminal proceedings.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The first holder of the office was Lynda Clark, then Member of Parliament for Edinburgh Pentlands and from 2005 a member of the House of Lords as Baroness Clark of Calton.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 18 January 2006, Baroness Clark resigned to take up office as a Senator of the College of Justice, a judge of the Supreme Courts of Scotland.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office was then vacant until 15 March of that year when, under section 87 of the Scotland Act 1998, its functions were temporarily conferred on the Secretary of State for Scotland, Alistair Darling MP, himself a Scottish advocate.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] There had been substantial criticism from the judiciary and others of the length of time the office had been left vacant.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 21 March, however, it was announced Neil Davidson, former Solicitor General for Scotland, had been appointed Advocate General.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Davidson of Glen Clova, on 22 March 2006.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 14 May 2010, Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness, a former Deputy First Minister of Scotland, was appointed by the coalition government.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Richard Keen was appointed Advocate General in David Cameron's majority government on 29 May 2015, and has retained the post through two subsequent prime ministers to 2020.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Keen of Elie, on 8 June 2015.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He resigned on 16 September 2020 citing concerns arising from the UK Internal Market Bill, noting in his letter of resignation to Boris Johnson that he found it "increasingly difficult to reconcile what I consider to be my obligations as a Law Officer with your policy intentions".
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Keith Stewart was appointed to succeed Keen on 15 October 2020.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Catherine Smith was appointed to the office and a life peerage by the Starmer government on 29 August 2024.
[src:advocate-general-for-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] All staff are on secondment or loan from other government organisations, mainly the Scottish Government and the Ministry of Justice.
